        Chart Review 20/09/24

        I swear everytime I talk about Fred Again.. my upload doesn't work-

        OH. HI. YOU MISSED ME? good. Last week I wasn't allowed to tell you about how boring Central Cee is, how lukewarm Alex Warren is, how David Gilmour popping up in the Viral 50 Spotify chart is a sign that prog-rock is still lurching around like it's World War Z, and why Linkin Park have suddenly transformed into Riot-era Paramore, probably due to the presence of some dance producer who headlined Reading and Leeds or whatever. At least, I think I did. Two of my other rankings have been scuppered surely because of 'places to be' in the Top 40, so I will refrain from mentioning any of his other future hits by name until the end of time.

        And no, that joke won't get annoying by the time he spends ages at No.1 in 2028.

        But you don't care about that right? We're here for the CURRENT Top 40, not the one we'll be gawking over in a few years time. And for the first time in ages there's actually some fresh new blood to sample in this week's biggest and best. A whopping SEVEN (if this was 1999 this would be low) new entries have made their way past the notoriously fickle general public and into our lives, and it is my job to document all of their feelings on camera. Except this is in word format, so I can't show up the sign I'm holding saying "NOAH KAHAN IS FINALLY GONE". You did notice that, yeah?

        No one is good enough to stop Sabrina Carpenter though (who is), as you can make that Week Number 4 for Taste at the summit of the UK chingaling, thus depriving us yet again the opportunity to praise Chappell Roan for the millionth time. At least she's responsible for one of the new hits, Red Wine Supernova crumbling to ACR and in it's place comes the equally popular Pink Pony Club at 21. It may be not as good as her other efforts, but I'd take this ballad over a dozen GagaMars collabs. No matter how much makeup they put on their faces in the video.

        But moving on from the inevitable backlash I'll get for not conforming to society, two so-called 'heavyweights' made their grand returns last week, and they've predictably performed better than all the other new shizzle they fought against. And powering it's way to 12 is the comeback single of the most indecisive musician I know. I have mixed feelings about The Weeknd, you see. For every stone-cold classic in his repertoire like Starboy, Can't Feel My Face and Sacrifice, he sure does have a lot of guff. Popular. That Kanye West song he was on that one time. The omnipresent Blinding Lights. Die For You. One Of The Girls. The list goes on and on with Canada's only hope. What with Justin Bieber forgetting he has a musical career and Drake trying his damndest not to get cancelled, it's up to Abel Tesfaye and the awful TV series he stars in to try and win us over. Except this isn't some Idol-related baloney. This is a new material he's got under his sleeve. And I am whole-heartedly shocked to say that I can update that stone-cold classic category once again because Dancing In The Flames is actually really good. Yeah, I know. Shock horror. Maybe he can have some legitimate success without looking like the people listening to him just have his music on at work 24 hours a day in a desperate attempt to give him hits. You know, like the BTS people. It's just a shame he's fallen off a cliff on Spotify though.

        Two places below him is another Maple Leaf-wielding chart star praying for relevancy, Calgary's own Tate McRae. This time last year we had to kickback and realise that greedy was gonna spend AGES in the Top 10. And you don't end up as one of 3 normal songs in a Christmas-themed chart without doing something right. So yeah, Tate's back, with her voice that Mimi Webb plagiarises for a living, and so are the wonky beats that make you think Nicki Minaj never left us. It's good, it's whatever, it deserves it's spot in the Top 20 for sure. I just get this horrendous feeling that she'll be rooted in the charts for ages and no amount of surprise reunions can unwedge. Given all the Oasis songs have tumbled into oblivion (aka the bottom half), that seems really likely.

        Gracie Abrams is Top 20 now but I don't have anything constructive to say.

        In at 24 is the latest remix from Charli XCX and her 'BRAT but I can't stop spending all my money on artists who look like Vogue models so it's not' phase of remixes that propelled her to No.1 last month with Guess, and this time it's former No.47 smash Talk Talk that invites Troye Sivan along for the ride to make a song that isn't as good as her other ones. To nobody's surprise then. Also Dua Lipa's here as well saying some French and Spanish words but I couldn't be bothered going back to check. And in other news, Teddy Swims clearly is the new Rag'n'Bone Man because he WON'T GO AWAY. You'd think having 2 songs in the best-sellers week in, week out would be bad enough right? Well no. 'Cos he's back lads. Run for your lives. Bad Dreams is gonna be all over Magic and Heart this Autumn and there's nothing you can do 'bout the matter. Thank the lord Spotify has deserted him so he's limped to 28.

        Hitting the charts at 32 is one of The Weeknd's many collaborators. In fact, it's long overdue that Playboi Carti had some solo success given he's been on every rap feature under the sun as of late. Popular, EARFQUAKE, CARNIVAL, FE!N, you name it, he's probably there, Just a shame that ALL RED isn't worth the wait, and instead sounds like something a 33-year old from Croydon thinks is 'hip'. Doesn't he knows it's all about singer-songwriters with perms now? Oh, and rocketing up from 75 to 36 is Embrace It, the first appearance from Angola-born Ndotz, whose claim to fame is that he was in a video of a Top 10 hit from 5 years ago no one remembers. Do you? Because I know what it is, and it couldn't be more forgettable. Also, this song vaguely reminds me of Bad Boy Chiller Crew, HStikkyTokky, K.A.D and all the other 'lad' dance hits that's so objectifying and stereotypey that it's ridiculous.

        Gun Lean by RUSS if anyone's interested.

        Top of the albums is everyone's favourite band to hate back in the 2000s, the Scottish/Irish/Who Knows Anymore gents of Snow Patrol. For years, they were stuck hanging out with Belle & Sebastian and making the kind of indie that nowadays probably wouldn't sound out of place in today's market. And then they got famous, and everything just kinda stank since then. They haven't made a good song since 2009. Chasing Cars was, and still is, atrocious. Don't get me started on their latter material. It's been 13 years since they last had any Top 40 success. Therefore, I don't care that The Forest Is The Path is their first No.1 album since 2006. From what I've heard, the singles are dull, dreary, and way too soggy. So just like my pencil, there's no point discussing them any further. There just isn't.

        Nines, Surf Curse, Odetari, nimino and Eminem also have hits on this chart but I don't have time to talk more thoroughly on them. But next week we get to see Blossoms, Katy Perry, Keith Urban, Tom Walker and Jamie beat each other to dust on the albums, meanwhile we have new songs from Future, Ava Max, Bad Bunny, Potter Payper and Tom Grennan to ignore for the rest of our lives. See you next week when I struggle to deal with my college assignments.
